	<Language_en_US>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_UNIT_SMAN_EU_SIEGE_ELEPHANT">
			<Text>[ICON_IDEOLOGY_AUTOCRACY] Siege Elephant</Text>
		</Row>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_UNIT_SMAN_EU_SIEGE_ELEPHANT_HELP">
			<Text>Hulking late-Classical Era Siege Weapon capable of quickly attacking Cities, but weak to Spearmen and Pikemen.</Text>
		</Row>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_UNIT_SMAN_EU_SIEGE_ELEPHANT_STRATEGY">
			<Text>Siege Elephant Strategy</Text>
		</Row>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_UNIT_SMAN_EU_SIEGE_ELEPHANT_PEDIA">
			<Text>
				The Siege Elephant is a late-Classical Era ranged unit, available at the discovery of Engineering. It becomes obsolete at the discovery of Chemistry, at which time it may upgrade to the Cannon unit.[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]The use of multibow siege crossbows is unique to East Asia. The very first arcuballistae were understandably single bow crossbows, emerging in the Warring States period of China. The technology was introduced into Indochina in AD 1171 when an emissary from the Song Dynasty travelled to Champa to trade the technology in exchange for privileges along the many trade routes Champa controlled in the South Sea. The Cham applied this technological innovation in siege warfare by mounting the arcuballistae on the backs of elephants.[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]Not long after this date, double-bow arcuballistae appear in 13th century Khmer bas-relief sculptures on the walls of Bayon and at Banteay Chmar. The Khmer adopted the technology from Champa either through a later trade agreement or from captured Cham soldiers and ballista elephant during their many wars for supremacy over the Indochina region. Siege crossbows, both standalone and mounted, were frequently used by both the Khmer and Champa in their wars with each other.
			</Text>
		</Row>
	</Language_en_US>
  
